KommentarENG: Rats are omnivores. But they eat a predominantly vegetarian diet. They eat up to twelve meals a day - most of them in the evening and at night. Die AfD nutzt hÃ¤ufig die Strategie der Angstmacherei, um WÃ¤hler zu mobilisieren. Indem sie Ã„ngste vor Migration, wirtschaftlichen Unsicherheiten und sozialem Abstieg schÃ¼rt, versucht sie, sich als Retter in der Not darzustellen. Diese Art der Politik zielt darauf ab, einfache Antworten auf komplexe Probleme zu geben. Sie bietet oft keine tiefgehenden oder durchdachten LÃ¶sungen an, sondern verlÃ¤sst sich auf populistische und plakative Aussagen.

Ein Beispiel ist die Migrationspolitik: WÃ¤hrend die AfD rigorose AbschottungsmaÃŸnahmen fordert, bleibt unklar, wie sie die Integration bereits hier lebender Menschen gestalten mÃ¶chte oder wie sie internationale Verpflichtungen einhalten will. Ã„hnlich sieht es bei wirtschaftlichen Themen aus. Die Partei kritisiert Globalisierung und EU-Politik, ohne jedoch realistische Alternativen oder umfassende Konzepte fÃ¼r wirtschaftliches Wachstum und soziale Gerechtigkeit vorzulegen.

Diese einfache Rhetorik mag auf den ersten Blick attraktiv erscheinen, verkennt jedoch die KomplexitÃ¤t der realen Probleme. KommentarENG:
The AfD often uses the strategy of fear-mongering to mobilize voters. By stoking fears about migration, economic uncertainty and social decline, it tries to portray itself as a savior in times of need. This type of politics aims to provide simple answers to complex problems. It often does not offer deep or well-thought-out solutions, but relies on populist and catchy statements.

One example is migration policy: While the AfD calls for rigorous isolation measures, it remains unclear how it intends to organize the integration of people already living here or how it intends to comply with international obligations. The situation is similar with economic issues. The party criticizes globalization and EU policy, but without presenting realistic alternatives or comprehensive concepts for economic growth and social justice.

This simple rhetoric may seem attractive at first glance, but it fails to recognize the complexity of the real problems. Voters should be aware that sustainable and effective solutions require more than mere slogans and fear-mongering. It is important to support politicians and parties who seriously address the challenges and offer well-thought-out concepts.

WOMEN CANNOT VOTE FOR THE AFD
Press release | March 7, 2024

For over a hundred years, women have been fighting for their rights on March 8. From the first joint protest in 1911 to today, women's movements have fought for one democratic right after another with iron determination and persistence. In the super election year of 2024, the German Women's Council warns of the immediate threat to these women's political achievements posed by the enormous support for right-wing populists and extremists. It calls on people to vote for democratic parties that want to protect and strengthen women's rights.

"In its programs, the AfD makes no secret of its backward-looking images of women and families: It wants to roll back hard-won progress in women's policy and reinstall the heteronormative nuclear family with a male head. It wants inequality and the restoration of a supposedly natural, patriarchal order," warns the chairwoman of the German Women's Council, Dr. Beate von Miquel.

This year, the EU Parliament will be elected in three eastern German federal states and numerous municipalities. This means that 2024 threatens to be a fateful year for women's and human rights: surveys predict that the European Parliament, as the heart of European democracy, will slide further to the right and that right-wing parties could also celebrate electoral successes in the federal states.

The AfD has never hidden its misanthropic positions. Most recently, the party confirmed its willingness to implement its racist fantasies of a nationalist nation - with mass expulsions of people who have lived in Germany for generations.

"We expect the same in the area of â€‹â€‹women's rights. Women's rights are the only reliable shield for women against patriarchal dominance, as envisaged by the AfD. The party will not shy away from taking away these rights bit by bit. We must be clear: democracy and women's rights are not given to us. We must defend them together - on March 8th and every other day!", continued von Miquel.

According to the AfD, the transport associations should generate half of their costs themselves. This can only be achieved by increasing ticket prices by over 50%. Or by having even fewer buses and trains.
Source: AfD Hessen 2023 election manifesto, line 1593
The AfD wants all employees to only retire without deductions after 45 years of contributions. But for 40% of all employees, this means working until they are 70! For women, this even affects half.
Source: afdbundestag.de/ eckpunktepapier-alterssicherung
The AfD is against looking after small children in daycare centers. Instead, parents should take over the care themselves for the first three years.
Source: AfD Hessen 2023 election manifesto, from line 379
The AfD is against inheritance and wealth taxes and wants to relieve the burden on high earners in particular. Source: AfD Federal Election Program 2021, page 36

The AfD wants to exclude children with mental and physical disabilities from regular schools.

Source: AfD Hesse Election Program 2023, line 545

The AfD wants to strictly limit immigration to highly qualified people. However, training young refugees is an important contribution to combating the growing shortage of trainees.

Source: AfD Bavaria Election Program, Chapter 5 (Asylum and Migration), 1st paragraph

Instead of promoting climate protection, the AfD wants to let climate change take its course.

Due to its effects, many insurers are already raising their rates. Source: AfD Bavaria election manifesto, Chapter 6 (Energy), 5th paragraph

The AfD rejects legal equality as

"unconstitutional discrimination".

Instead, it wants to encourage women to stay at home and raise their children.

Source: AfD Bavaria election manifesto, Chapter 17 (Social Policy), 6th paragraph

The AfD wants to abolish the rent cap and the rent index.
This will allow landlords to increase rents significantly more than before.

Sources: AfD Hesse 2023 election manifesto, line 1686 and statement by the AfD parliamentary group in the Hesse state parliament

In its manifesto for the European elections, the AfD calls for the establishment of a federation of European nations that emphasizes the sovereignty of the member states and wants to abolish the European Parliament. However, this position has several disadvantages for Germany and its citizens:

1. **Economic instability**: Leaving the EU, as the AfD is striving for, could lead to significant economic losses. Experts warn that Germany's gross domestic product (GDP) could fall by as much as 5.6% in such a scenario. Economic integration and free access to the European internal market are key drivers of German prosperity, and a "Dexit" would jeopardize this access.

2. **Political isolation**: By abolishing the European Parliament and restricting EU competences, Germany would massively reduce its political influence at the European level. The ability to actively shape European politics and represent national interests in the EU would be severely restricted. This could lead to Germany becoming isolated and mean the loss of important alliances and cooperation.

3. **Loss of funding**: The EU provides Germany and other member states with extensive funding for infrastructure, research and development, and social projects. The loss of these funds would hit structurally weak regions particularly hard and could further exacerbate social inequality in the country.

"Our country first!" Doesn't that sound wonderfully retro? The AfD wants a 'federation of European nations' that sounds like the EU, only without its advantages. But who needs advantages when you have sovereignty as the magic word?

4. **Art der gelieferten Waffen**: Deutschland hat der Ukraine zahlreiche Verteidigungssysteme, Artillerie und Drohnen geliefert, die der ukrainischen Armee helfen, sich gegen Angriffe zu verteidigen und zivile Infrastrukturen zu schÃ¼tzen. The AfD claims that the arms deliveries to Ukraine have only brought suffering and destruction and instead calls for negotiations. However, this portrayal ignores essential facts about the situation in Ukraine.

1. **Need for defense**: Ukraine is defending itself against an invasion by Russia that violates international law. Without military support, Ukraine's ability to defend itself would be severely limited, which could lead to major humanitarian disasters.

2. **International legal basis**: The delivery of weapons to Ukraine is covered by international law and does not constitute warmongering. The German Justice Minister confirmed that these deliveries are legally permissible and are not considered direct participation in the war.

3. **Broad support and responsibility**: European leaders, including French President Emmanuel Macron, emphasize the need to support Ukraine in the long term to ensure stability and peace in Europe. Without this support, a Russian victory could have significant negative consequences for the whole of Europe.

4. **Type of weapons supplied**: Germany has supplied Ukraine with numerous defense systems, artillery and drones that help the Ukrainian army defend itself against attacks and protect civilian infrastructure. These weapons are crucial for repelling air strikes and for defending against armored units of the aggressor.

The AfD's call for an immediate negotiated peace ignores the fact that Russia has so far shown little willingness to seriously negotiate a fair peace. Peace negotiations can only be successful if both sides are willing to conduct them in good faith and respect Ukraine's sovereignty and territorial integrity.

The AfD's call to limit the power of the EU and create a federation of European nations has several disadvantages, both economic and political.

1. **Economic disadvantages**: 
- **Trade barriers**: Limiting EU power could lead to trade barriers as the harmonized rules for the internal market could be eliminated. This could make trade between member states more difficult and weaken the economy as a whole.
- **Investments and labor market**: The EU offers German companies access to a large market and facilitates investments. Weakening the EU could lead to a reduction in foreign investment and destabilize the labor market. Many German jobs depend directly or indirectly on access to the European market.

2. **Political disadvantages**: 
- **International influence**: The EU enables its member states to collectively have a stronger voice on the global stage. A return to greater national sovereignty could weaken Germany's position in international negotiations and affect its ability to tackle global challenges such as climate change.
- **Legal uncertainty**: AfD proposals to disempower the European Court of Justice could lead to legal uncertainty. The ECJ plays a crucial role in enforcing EU law and protecting the rights of EU citizens. Weakening this court could reduce citizens' legal protections and jeopardize the coherence of the internal market.

Solche Kritik richtet sich jedoch nicht pauschal gegen grÃ¼ne Politik, sondern gegen spezifische Entscheidungen, die aus Sicht der NaturschutzverbÃ¤nde nachteilige Auswirkungen auf die Umwelt haben kÃ¶nnten.

KommentarENG:
The AfD's claim that NABU and BUND warn against green politics is misleading and false. NABU and BUND generally support environmental protection measures that are often promoted by green parties.

1. **Alliance for Environmental Protection**: Both organizations regularly work with political parties to achieve common goals in environmental and nature conservation. NABU describes itself as a partner of politics in implementing these goals and supports numerous nature conservation projects that are realized with political support.

2. **Focus on nature conservation and sustainability**: BUND and NABU tend to criticize specific projects or measures that are not in line with sustainable environmental goals, such as the construction of wind turbines in sensitive natural locations or the instrumentalization of nature conservation agreements by political actors. However, such criticism is not directed against green politics in general, but against specific decisions that, from the point of view of nature conservation associations, could have adverse effects on the environment.

3. **Support for environmentally friendly policies**: Both organizations call for and support measures that strengthen biodiversity and combat climate change, which often coincides with the political programs of green parties. For example, they support initiatives to redesign green spaces in a more natural way and to promote insect populations, which is in line with the goals of many green programs.

Overall, the facts show that NABU and BUND can criticize specific projects or measures, but generally support the principles and goals of green policies if they serve the environment and nature conservation.

KommentarENG:
Good for the rich - bad for everyone who has less!

To attract voters, the AfD repeatedly claims that it supports the "ordinary people". However, its positions often have the exact opposite effect: tax gifts for the rich and disadvantages for everyone else! 
For example, income tax: Currently, tax rates are individually tailored to income. Those who earn more pay a correspondingly higher tax rate. Instead, the AfD wants to introduce a few tax brackets, i.e. groups for which the same tax rates then apply. This benefits those whose income is below the limit of a tax bracket - just like with buses and trains: If the destination is still in zone A, everything is fine, but if the stop is directly behind the border to zone B, it becomes significantly more expensive. Tax brackets thus disadvantage people whose income just exceeds a limit. This makes the tax system simpler, but also more unfair. 
For example, wealth and inheritance tax: Currently, no wealth tax has to be paid. The AfD is committed to keeping it that way and abolishing wealth tax altogether. The state should also forego inheritance tax. But that would be socially unjust because wealth and inheritance tax are mainly paid by rich people, who also benefit much more from our society with its infrastructure and community. Abolishing these taxes means relieving the burden on those who already have enough at the expense of people with less wealth.

Conclusion: The AfD does not represent the "ordinary people", but the interests of the wealthy

Die Behauptung der AfD, dass der Atomausstieg der Hauptgrund fÃ¼r hohe Strompreise sei, lÃ¤sst sich durch aktuelle Daten widerlegen. 

1. **Strompreise nach Atomausstieg**
 
- Nach dem Atomausstieg sind die Strompreise an der BÃ¶rse nicht gestiegen, sondern gesunken. So berichtete die Bundesnetzagentur, dass die Preise im ersten Monat nach der Abschaltung der letzten Atomkraftwerke sogar gesunken sind. 
 
- Auch langfristig sind die Strompreise seit dem HÃ¶hepunkt der Energiekrise im Herbst 2022 erheblich gesunken. Damals lag der Preis bei bis zu 70 Cent pro Kilowattstunde, wÃ¤hrend er aktuell bei rund 26 Cent liegt.

2. **Erneuerbare Energien als Ersatz**
 
- Der Wegfall des deutschen Atomstroms wird grÃ¶ÃŸtenteils durch erneuerbare Energien wie Wind und Solar ausgeglichen. Diese Entwicklung hat den Strommarkt stabilisiert und zu geringeren Preisen beigetragen.

KommentarENG:
The AfD's claim that the nuclear phase-out is the main reason for high electricity prices can be refuted by current data. 

1. **Electricity prices after nuclear phase-out**

- After the nuclear phase-out, electricity prices on the stock exchange did not rise, but fell. The Federal Network Agency reported that prices actually fell in the first month after the last nuclear power plants were shut down. 

- In the long term, electricity prices have also fallen considerably since the peak of the energy crisis in autumn 2022. At that time, the price was up to 70 cents per kilowatt hour, while it is currently around 26 cents.

2. **Renewable energies as a replacement**

- The loss of German nuclear power is largely offset by renewable energies such as wind and solar. This development has stabilized the electricity market and contributed to lower prices.

- Contrary to the claim that the nuclear phase-out was a "wrong decision", reports show that the impact of the shut down nuclear power plants on overall electricity production is relatively small and has been compensated by other measures and energy sources. 

3. **Imports and security of supply**

- Germany does import some electricity, but this is more a question of pricing than availability. Electricity is imported from neighboring countries such as France when their electricity production is cheaper, not because Germany has a lack of generation capacity. 

- Security of supply in Germany is still guaranteed after the nuclear phase-out. Reports from the Federal Network Agency confirm that there is no increased risk of power outages. 

In summary, the nuclear phase-out is not the main reason for high electricity prices. Rather, renewable energies are helping to stabilize the electricity market and lower prices. Security of supply is also guaranteed, which means that the AfD's arguments are not valid in this context.

Merz und Co. haben klar signalisiert, dass sie die aktuellen Herausforderungen mit anderen Partnern lÃ¶sen mÃ¶chten. Spekulationen Ã¼ber geheime BÃ¼ndnisse sind also nicht nur haltlos, sondern auch kontraproduktiv.

2. Diese Behauptung, dass die CDU mit den GrÃ¼nen an der Regierung automatisch zu â€illegaler Massenmigrationâ€œ und â€zerstÃ¶rerischer Energiepolitikâ€œ fÃ¼hrt, ist ein MÃ¤rchen, das nur in bestimmten Kreisen Anklang findet. Faktencheck: Die Abschiebungsquote ist in einigen von der CDU regierten BundeslÃ¤ndern sogar gestiegen. Und die Energiepolitik? Da gibt es diverse Meinungen, aber zu behaupten, dass die GrÃ¼nen allein die Verantwortung tragen, ist einfach falsch.

3. Wer wirklich glaubt, dass Merkel die CDU noch steuert, lebt wohl in der Vergangenheit. Ihre Rolle in der Partei ist seit ihrem RÃ¼cktritt stark geschrumpft. Zusammengefasst: Hier wird wieder einmal mit Angst und Panik gearbeitet, um politische Stimmung zu machen. Eine Koalition mit den GrÃ¼nen steht heute nicht zur Debatte, und die CDU ist weit davon entfernt, grÃ¼ne Ideologien zu Ã¼bernehmen. Aber danke fÃ¼r die Unterhaltung!
KommentarENG:
Oh, how refreshing to see the same old bogeyman painted on the wall again. In fact, Friedrich Merz is currently talking about a completely different direction for the CDU. But as we all know, facts are not everyone's cup of tea.

1. The CDU has repeatedly emphasized in recent years that a coalition with the Greens is currently out of the question. Merz and Co. have clearly signaled that they want to solve the current challenges with other partners. Speculation about secret alliances is therefore not only baseless, but also counterproductive.

2. This claim that the CDU with the Greens in government automatically leads to "illegal mass migration" and "destructive energy policy" is a fairy tale that only resonates in certain circles. Fact check: The deportation rate has actually increased in some federal states governed by the CDU. And energy policy? There are various opinions on this, but to claim that the Greens alone are responsible is simply wrong.

3. Anyone who really believes that Merkel is still controlling the CDU is probably living in the past. Her role in the party has shrunk considerably since her resignation. The current CDU leadership under Merz is pursuing a completely different line that has little to do with the Greens. It is therefore pure fiction that the CDU is pursuing a green ideology.

In summary: This is once again using fear and panic to create a political mood. A coalition with the Greens is not up for debate today, and the CDU is far from adopting green ideologies. But thanks for the entertainment!

The AfD claims that it wants to protect women and girls. However, a closer look at the party program and the AfD's political positions shows that this statement is questionable.

1. **Traditional family image**: The AfD propagates a return to the "traditional family" consisting of father, mother and children. This concept largely excludes modern family models such as single parents and same-sex couples. In addition, the AfD rejects abortion and wants to severely restrict it, which would significantly impair women's self-determination.

2. **Anti-feminist attitude**: Leading AfD politicians regularly speak disparagingly about feminism and equate it with negative terms. For example, Bundestag member Nicole HÃ¶chst described feminism as "tit socialism" and denied the structural disadvantage of women. This attitude shows that the party has little interest in addressing the real problems of women in society.

3. **Focus on migration**: The AfD often uses the issue of women's protection to incite hatred against migrants. The party claims that the greatest danger to women comes from migrant men, which greatly distorts reality. This distracts from the real causes of violence against women, which often take place in the home and regardless of the perpetrators' origins.

4. **Rejection of women's rights**: In the Bundestag, the AfD has voted several times against laws intended to strengthen women's rights. This contradicts its claim to want to protect women and girls. In fact, its policies would further restrict many women's rights.

Overall, it is clear that the AfD's practices and political positions do little to improve the safety and rights of women and girls. Its measures and views seem more aimed at reinforcing traditional gender roles and inciting hatred against certain social groups.

Fact: EU citizens elect their representatives to the European Parliament every five years. This parliament has extensive powers, including legislation, budgetary control and control over the EU Commission.

The AfD's campaign ad for the European elections contains several claims and criticisms of the EU that do not stand up to closer scrutiny. Here are some of the most important statements and the corresponding facts that refute them:

1. Claim: â€œEurope means the EU, which consists only of bureaucratsâ€

Fact: The EU is not just made up of bureaucrats. The EU Commission employs around 32,000 people, which is relatively small compared to national administrations. 2. Claim: â€œThe EU regulates unnecessary things like the size of pizzas and the brightness of lightbulbsâ€

Fact: EU regulations aim to protect consumers and harmonize the internal market. For example, the energy efficiency guidelines for light bulbs have helped reduce energy consumption and CO2 emissions, which makes both ecological and economic sense.

3. Claim: â€œInvestigations against Ursula von der Leyen on suspicion of corruption in vaccine dealsâ€

Fact: There have been no formal investigations against Ursula von der Leyen on suspicion of corruption. The European Public Prosecutor's Office is generally investigating the handling of public funds, but there are no specific charges against her in connection with the vaccine deals.

This post is not only oversimplified and polemical, but also misleading and dangerous. Here are some facts that refute the statements and undermine the slogan "deportations are women's protection":

1. Gang rape figures: According to the Police Crime Statistics (PKS) for Berlin, far fewer than 111 gang rapes were reported in 2022. The exact number is well below the 111 cases claimed here. This kind of fear-mongering only serves to incite panic and reinforce prejudices.

2. Origin of suspects: The PKS shows that 54% of suspects are foreign nationals. However, this number must be viewed in context. Many factors contribute to crime, including social and economic circumstances. It is misleading to blame foreigners for crime across the board and thereby stigmatize an entire population group.

3. Political measures: Both the federal government and the Berlin Senate have taken a wide range of measures to increase security and promote integration. These include increased police presence, prevention programs and integration projects. These measures are comprehensive and aim to combat the causes of crime rather than just treating symptoms.

4. Migration and crime: Studies such as those by the German Institute for Economic Research (DIW) and the Federal Criminal Police Office (BKA) show that there is no simple correlation between migration and crime. Crime often has complex causes that go beyond origin. It is therefore dangerous and misleading to present deportations as a panacea for solving security problems.

KommentarENG: According to the AfD, the transport associations should generate half of their costs themselves. This can only be achieved by increasing ticket prices by over 50%. Or by having even fewer buses and trains. Source: AfD Hessen election manifesto 2023, line 1593 The AfD wants all employees to only retire without deductions after 45 years of contributions. But for 40% of all employees, this means working until they are 70! For women, this even affects half. Source: afdbundestag.de/eckpunktepapier-alterssicherung The AfD is against the care of small children in daycare centers. Instead, parents should take over the care themselves in the first three years. Source: AfD Hessen election manifesto 2023, from line 379. The AfD is against inheritance and wealth taxes and wants to relieve the burden on high earners in particular. Source: AfD federal election manifesto 2021, page 36. The AfD wants to exclude children with mental and physical disabilities from regular schools. Source: AfD Hessen election manifesto 2023, line 545. The AfD wants to strictly limit immigration to highly qualified people. The training of young refugees is, however, an important contribution to combating the growing shortage of trainees. Source: AfD Bavaria election manifesto, Chapter 5 (AsyI and Migration), 1st paragraph. Instead of promoting climate protection, the AfD wants to let climate change take its course. Because of its effects, many insurers are already raising their rates. Source: AfD Bavaria election manifesto Chapter 6 (Energy), 5th paragraph. The AfD rejects legal equality as unconstitutional discrimination. Instead, it wants to encourage women to stay at home and raise their children. Source: AfD Bavaria election manifesto Chapter 17 (Social Policy), 6th paragraph. The AfD wants to abolish the rent cap and the rent index. KommentarENG:
I am now putting forward a thesis: Yes, most AfD voters are angry about the current government policies. That is why they tend to vote for the AfD. However, I am convinced that the majority of these voters do not really know what the AfD's party program says and how to interpret it. They are guided by the simple, populist phrases and react to the fears that the AfD stirs up in them.

A worrying phenomenon that I often observe is that many of these voters simply repeat what the AfD tells them. They are unable to reproduce or analyze the contents of the AfD's party program on their own. These people live in a bubble that is exclusively shaped by the AfD's information. They get their information mainly from portals and social media that are influenced by the AfD and thus have a distorted view of the world. What happens outside this bubble is either ignored or dismissed as a lie because the AfD has implanted this perception deep into their consciousness.

The long-term consequences of this behavior are alarming. Ultimately, these people will find themselves in a reality in which they are worse off than before. But by then it will be too late to change anything, as democratic structures may already have been dismantled and the Basic Law changed in favor of the AfD. 

There are numerous warnings about the dangers posed by the AfD. Perhaps we should all seriously consider whether there is any truth in these warnings. It is important to critically examine political content and not blindly follow populist slogans. Because, as already said: afterwards it is too late. 

An enlightened and informed citizenry is the backbone of a functioning democracy. We all have a responsibility to inform ourselves comprehensively and to consider the consequences of our political actions. This is the only way we can ensure that our society remains free, fair and democratic.
